\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}
\paragraph{Primary Equation.}
\begin{equation}
H
=
\frac{p^2}{2m}
+
\frac{1}{2}m\omega^2 q^2
+
\delta H .
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Ladder Constraint.}
\begin{equation}
[a,a^\dagger]=1 .
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}
The ordinary quantum harmonic oscillator has Hamiltonian:

\begin{equation}
H_0
=
\frac{p^2}{2m}
+
\frac{1}{2}m\omega^2 q^2 .
\end{equation}

Near the TZP, curvature-sensitive or zero-point corrections are collected into a perturbative term $\delta H$:

\begin{equation}
H = H_0+\delta H .
\end{equation}

Substituting $H_0$ gives:

\begin{equation}
\boxed{
H
=
\frac{p^2}{2m}
+
\frac{1}{2}m\omega^2 q^2
+
\delta H .
}
\end{equation}

The ladder algebra remains admissible if the correction preserves the oscillator structure:

\begin{equation}
[a,a^\dagger]=1 .
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Interpretation.}
The TZP-modified oscillator keeps the standard oscillator core while adding a curvature-sensitive correction.
% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER
